        <title>Demo: Section NM</title>

        <frontmatter xml:id="index">
            <titlepage>
                <author>
                    <personname>Robert Beezer</personname>
                    <department>Department of Mathematics and Computer Science</department>
                    <institution>University of Puget Sound</institution>
                </author>
                <!-- <xi:include href="course-term.xml" /> -->  <!-- a date element -->
                <date>Math 290, Spring 2016</date>
            </titlepage>
        </frontmatter>

            <p>First, a nonsingular <m>5\times 5</m> matrix, created at random.</p>

            <sage>
                <input>
                A = random_matrix(QQ, 5, algorithm="unimodular", upper_bound=20)
                A
                </input>
            </sage>


            <p>Augment with the zero vector and row-reduce (Definition NM), or don't augment (Theorem NMRRI).</p>

            <sage />

            <p>Build some random vectors, augment and row-reduce.  Always a unique solution to the linear system represented by the augmented matrix.</p>

            <sage />

            <p>Cheap, easy and powerful:</p>

            <sage>
                <input>A.is_singular()</input>
            </sage>

            <p>Now, a carefully crafted singular matrix.</p>

            <sage>
                <input>
                B = matrix(QQ, [[7,-1,-12,21,-8], [-3,3,0,-9,6], [3,3,-12,9,0], [2,3,-10,6,1], [-2,2,0,-6,4]])
                B
                </input>
            </sage>


            <p>Augment with the zero vector and row-reduce (Definition NM), or don't augment (Theorem NMRRI).</p>

            <sage />

            <p>Cheap, easy and powerful:</p>

            <sage>
                <input>B.is_singular()
                </input>
            </sage>

            <p>Two carefully crafted vectors for linear systems with <c>B</c> as coefficient matrix.</p>

            <sage>
                <input>
                c = vector(QQ, [17,-15,-3,-5,-10])
                d = vector(QQ, [-3,1,-2,1,2])
                </input>
            </sage>

            <p>Which column vectors will create consistent systems? (Stay tuned.)</p>

            <sage />

            <p>A null space is called a <q>right kernel</q> in Sage.</p>

            <sage>
                <input>
                NS = B.right_kernel()
                NS.list()
                </input>
            </sage>

            <p>We can test membership in the null space.</p>

            <sage>
                <input>u = vector(QQ, [0,0,3,4,6])</input>
            </sage>

            <sage />

            <sage>
                <input>v = vector(QQ, [1,0,0,5,-2])</input>
            </sage>

            <sage />

